475","about 1495":"circa 1495","1549":"1549","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1475–":"about 1475–Deceased","1475–Male":"1475–Deceased","1495–1545":"1495–1545","1475–Female":"1475–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1475":"1475","about 1499":"about 1499","1495":"1495","1571":"1571","about 1475":"about 1475","about 1495":"about 1495","1549":"1549","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salmon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and French: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Salmon</i>, <i>Saumon</i>, a shortened form of <i>Salomon</i> (see   Solomon  ). The Normans introduced it to England, and it was current as a personal name there until at least the end of the 14th century. The derived surname is found throughout 13th- and 14th-century England, mostly in the spellings <i>Saleman</i> and <i>Salman</i>, which eventually became regularized as <i>Salmon</i>. See also 2 below, compare   Salman   3.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname for someone ‘as wise as Solomon’. In Chaucer's <i>Canon's Yeoman's Tale</i>, it is stated: ‘And whan we been togidres euerichoon, Euery man semeth a Salomon’. King   Solomon   was famed for his wisdom.","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>salmon</i>, <i>saumo(u)n</i>, <i>saumun</i>, <i>samoun</i> ‘salmon’, no doubt given to someone who caught, sold, or ate the fish."],"variants":[{"name":"Sammon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","English and Irish (Mayo): variant of   Salmon  ."]},{"name":"Salmen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Wilhelm, Ilse.","English (Middlesex) and German: variant of English   Salmon   or Swiss German   Salman  ."]},{"name":"Salmons","meanings":["English: variant of   Salmon  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Salmond","meanings":["Scottish (Angus and Fife) and English: variant of   Salmon   1, with excrescent <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Salman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammad, Salman, Faisal, Ahmad, Amira, Imad, Issam, Khalid, Mohamed, Mohammed, Moosa, Omar.","Muslim: from a personal name based on Arabic <i>salmān</i> ‘safe’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Salmon   5."]},{"name":"Solomon","meanings":["Jewish, English, Scottish, Dutch, Swedish, French, Portuguese, Romanian, Ethiopian, and Eritrean; Spanish (<b>Solomón</b>): from a vernacular form of the Biblical Hebrew personal name <i>Shelomo</i>, a derivative of <i>shalom</i> ‘peace’. The name <i>Solomon</i> has for generations been a popular Jewish name and was also fairly widespread in the Middle Ages among Christians. In the Bible it is the name of King David's successor, noted for his wisdom; among Christians it was therefore also used as a nickname for a man who was considered wise. The spelling <i>Solomon</i> is used in the King James Bible of 1611, which is why this is the standard form of the name in modern English, but spellings with <i>Sal-</i> were more usual across continental Europe, the 1534 Lutheran Bible rendering it as <i>Salomo</i> and the 1560 Geneva Bible as   Salomon  . From the 7th century the spelling <i>Salomon</i> is recorded as a Christian personal name in France, where it was the name of several saints including a Breton king martyred in 874. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages (see   Salomon  ,   Salamon  ). See also   Salmon   1. — Note: Since Ethiopians and Eritreans do not have hereditary surnames, the Ethiopian and Eritrean name was registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Zalman","meanings":["Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Salmon   5."]},{"name":"Salkin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Salkin</i>, probably a pet form (with the Flemish and Middle English diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>) of <i>Salomon</i> (see   Salmon   and   Solomon  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish personal name <i>Zalkind</i>, derived from   Salomon  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":74,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":83,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":94,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":96,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. John Salmon 